WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.750 --> 00:00:04.770
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.130 --> 00:00:24.430
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Welcome viewers.

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:27.800
My name is Dan Sheehy,
Director and Curator Emeritus

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:30.180
of Smithsonian Folkways Recordings.

00:00:30.180 --> 00:00:33.630
And it's my pleasure to have
been here today at a concert

00:00:33.630 --> 00:00:36.970 position:56%
in the Library of Congress sponsored
by the American Folklife Center

00:00:36.970 --> 00:00:41.680
that featured three extraordinary
musicians from Albuquerque,

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:44.920
New Mexico, at least
where they live right now.

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:49.370
A trio lead by the great
oudist from Baghdad originally

00:00:49.370 --> 00:00:51.440
and now a long-time
American citizen,

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:55.240
refugee from the Saddam
Hussein regime playing oud,

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:56.540
composer as well.

00:00:56.540 --> 00:01:01.130
Just recorded a new
album coming out in 2017

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:03.360
with Smithsonian Folkways
Recordings,

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:07.300
accompanied by Sourena
Sefati, a Persian oud--

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:10.740
sorry, a Persian santour player.

00:01:10.740 --> 00:01:16.150 position:56%
Santour is one of my most favorite
instruments in the world by the way;

00:01:16.150 --> 00:01:17.830
I hope you enjoy it as well.

00:01:17.830 --> 00:01:19.570
He also lives in Albuquerque.

00:01:19.570 --> 00:01:22.760
He's been there a little
over a year from Iran,

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:26.980
and also the great percussionist
and discipline and protégé

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:31.220
of Rahim AlHaj, Issa
Malluf, playing a host

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:33.270
of different musical instruments.

00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:38.670
And now, it's a great pleasure
for me to ask you to join us

00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:43.130
in a conversation with the
great oudist, Rahim AlHaj.

00:01:43.130 --> 00:01:46.610
Rahim, it's great to
be together again.

00:01:46.610 --> 00:01:50.310
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: It's great to be
with you always amigo, you know?

00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:51.610
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Yes.

00:01:51.610 --> 00:01:53.320
I especially like this
very elegant stage setting.

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:54.620
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Isn't it?

00:01:54.620 --> 00:01:55.920
This is [inaudible]?

00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:57.220
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Like we're
really indulged with it.

00:01:57.220 --> 00:01:58.520
[ Laughter ]

00:01:58.520 --> 00:01:59.820
So, listen.

00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:01.120
So, we've talked many times before

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:04.930
but I don't think we ever
really talked about, you know,

00:02:04.930 --> 00:02:07.140
just right from the
basics, you know.

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:10.610
Like for example, tell us
about, what was it like--

00:02:10.610 --> 00:02:12.690
what family were you born into?

00:02:12.690 --> 00:02:14.920
You know, what was it like
family life when you are young

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:16.220
as far as you can remember?

00:02:16.220 --> 00:02:20.070
Where was it-- You know, what
was day to day life like, as--

00:02:20.070 --> 00:02:21.370
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Yeah.

00:02:21.370 --> 00:02:22.780
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: -- as far
back as you can remember?

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:29.000
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: I was born in
Iraq, Baghdad, in an area--

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.300
it's called the Thawra,
the revolution.

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:39.520
And for actually poor people
who are after the revolution

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:43.670
against the royalty's
family in Iraq.

00:02:43.670 --> 00:02:48.970
And so they give them--
each family are given one--

00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:53.610
or a person actually-- a piece
of land to build their house.

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:54.910
But it's limited.

00:02:54.910 --> 00:03:00.530
It's like 145 meters,
something like that.

00:03:00.530 --> 00:03:02.720
And we are-- I'm the
youngest of my family.

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:04.400
We are a big family actually.

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:09.850
I have five sisters
and two brothers.

00:03:09.850 --> 00:03:14.770
And, I was born as a
miricle like my mom said,

00:03:14.770 --> 00:03:17.550
because she had me when she was 45.

00:03:17.550 --> 00:03:22.990
And 45 during that time in
1968, is like a miracle.

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:26.160
No woman can get birth
through that time.

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:29.140
It could happen here and
there about within that frame

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:33.210 position:56%
of [inaudible] things its a miracle.

00:03:33.210 --> 00:03:37.550
So I'm born when I was for--
my mom like I said, 45.

00:03:37.550 --> 00:03:42.000
When I grow up, I don't remember
really my mom was my mom,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.310
because she's old.

00:03:43.310 --> 00:03:44.610
It's like my grandma.

00:03:44.610 --> 00:03:47.540
So my sisters-- they
took care of me.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:50.790
And that's what I think
they are my mother and that

00:03:50.790 --> 00:03:53.720
because she has white hair.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.920
And my mom is the most beautiful
woman I've ever really seen.

00:03:58.920 --> 00:04:08.190 position:56%
And, she's so wise to the point
like she framed and I gave her a lot

00:04:08.190 --> 00:04:12.500
of credit of making Rahim
AlHaj as a musician.

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:18.140
And my father was a typical
Middle Eastern father who is--

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:23.640
his power and his authority
has to be in a place

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:26.980
and the kids has to
follow the rules.

00:04:26.980 --> 00:04:29.330
And I call him the stick, actually.

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:35.930
So-- And my mom she's, you know,
is ruled that kind of house.

00:04:35.930 --> 00:04:39.390
And because I'm different
and because I was born

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:42.430
in different time, in
the wrong time, right,

00:04:42.430 --> 00:04:47.160
to my father according to my mom.

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:52.930
And so, I started my life
with this kind of environment

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:55.490
of beautiful people who
loves me and adore me

00:04:55.490 --> 00:04:57.390
because I'm the youngest, right?

00:04:57.390 --> 00:05:01.660
And I'm their toy because they
don't have kids that time.

00:05:01.660 --> 00:05:04.470
There's nobody.

00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:13.170
So, since-- then I started
my initiation to music.

00:05:13.170 --> 00:05:15.950
And like I said, again,
when my mom played a role--

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:23.260
a huge role in my music career and
my personality at the same time.

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:28.940
I remember so vividly, one
day when I was in practice--

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:32.370
I practice a lot and my
father doesn't need me

00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:35.570
to be a musician, never ever.

00:05:35.570 --> 00:05:43.050 position:56%
And in fact, I remember so vividly
that he hold a gun actually one time

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:45.180
and he put it to his head.

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:48.990
He said, "If you really continue
music, I'm going to kill myself."

00:05:48.990 --> 00:05:51.380
So, he needs me to
do something else.

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:52.800
And I did, actually.

00:05:52.800 --> 00:05:59.860
In fact, I went to-- And I studied
Arabic literature with music

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:01.160
in conservatory--

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:05.000
Baghdad Conservatory because
that's the only way I can continue

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.960
studying music.

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:11.030
But I remember my mom told him--
One day they have conversation

00:06:11.030 --> 00:06:16.820
and she told him, "Can you please
don't give this kid a hard time,

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:22.760 position:56%
because he will the most of
important oud player in the planet."

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:24.630
I don't know what that means,
really, when I'm a kid.

00:06:24.630 --> 00:06:26.700
I'm like seven years old, you know?

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:28.000
It's nothing.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.150
It doesn't come to
me what's that mean

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:34.780
that your mother can see
this potential for a musician

00:06:34.780 --> 00:06:36.590
in you and you have no idea.

00:06:36.590 --> 00:06:40.340
All I can do is to play the oud.

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:46.000
So, I remember one time,
I was practicing at night

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:55.270 position:56%
and usually I developed a really bad
habit sleeping with my instrument.

00:06:55.270 --> 00:06:58.850
I mean, I can't for five
years, I cannot go to sleep

00:06:58.850 --> 00:07:00.150
if I don't have my instrument.

00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:02.430
So I cover it with a blanket.

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:03.730
I kiss it.

00:07:03.730 --> 00:07:08.400
And one time I was there and I
was really tired and I was talking

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:11.610
to the oud, "I'm sorry
baby, I'm really tired.

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:14.630
So can we play tomorrow,"
and like that.

00:07:14.630 --> 00:07:17.670
And just like a real
person, you know?

00:07:17.670 --> 00:07:19.280
So I cover it and I
kiss it and I cover it

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:21.580
and was father was passing by.

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:26.770
And he went to my mom and
he said, "Our son is insane.

00:07:26.770 --> 00:07:29.620
We need to do something about it."

00:07:29.620 --> 00:07:31.310
So I'm like [inaudible].

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:36.570 position:56%
And-- So he really wasn't into music

00:07:36.570 --> 00:07:44.620
but he has the most beautiful
voice I've ever heard in my life.

00:07:44.620 --> 00:07:54.020
And when he sing, the depth
and the sensibility in it,

00:07:54.020 --> 00:08:00.270
he took this voice to cry.

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:07.470
Because he came from-- And my mom
at the same time, they are cousins.

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:12.200
It came from a Marsh
Arabs in the south.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:14.930
And the Marsh, as you
know, is just water, right?

00:08:14.930 --> 00:08:18.280 position:56%
That's how they-- and then when they
go to the boat from house to house

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:19.970
and there's the trees high.

00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:23.920
So that's where they use
their voice, singing.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:30.430
And he has absolutely
haunting voice, haunting.

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:35.280
I remember one time he was
singing and he went and grab my oud

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:39.330
and I want to know which kind
of maqam he used, you know,

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:41.620
what kind of maqam he sing to.

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:45.790
And my mom just stopped and
she said, "What are you doing?"

00:08:45.790 --> 00:08:47.340
I said, "What?

00:08:47.340 --> 00:08:48.640
I want play with him."

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:50.830
She said, "No, no, no, son.

00:08:50.830 --> 00:08:52.610
He is actually crying.

00:08:52.610 --> 00:08:55.800
Did you not see?"

00:08:55.800 --> 00:09:01.420
I said, "No wonder why this is so
deep in sound of sadness in it."

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:08.570
After that, actually I remember
my mom bought me the first suit

00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:09.870
when I went to perform.

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:14.660
I was in second grade
of-- in literature school.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:19.320
And, you know, suit and
something like that.

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:25.170
And my father never actually
came to any of my concerts.

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:27.370
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Can you remember
any of those songs that he sang?

00:09:27.370 --> 00:09:28.670
Can you sing any of them?

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:29.970
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Yeah, of course.

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:33.900
There's some maqams which
is really interesting

00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:36.780
and very important in
Iraq, specifically.

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:39.420
We use maqam as [inaudible].

00:09:39.420 --> 00:09:43.280
Now the south actually
is fascinating.

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:48.080
The maqam they use-- And that's my
theory when I did that in school,

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:55.060
when I was a student when I
graduated from a conservatory.

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:58.820
I did my paper of the difference
between the north and the south

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:03.440
over the maqam, how they
use it and how the Kurdish

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:10.150 position:56%
and the north they use are different
from people who lives in Ahwar,

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:13.280
which is the Marsh
Arab, for example.

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:19.840
So and then I figured
out that all these people

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:25.770
who create their own
style and their own voice

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:28.620 position:56%
but they have no idea what's called.

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:31.800
So when I go there, I said, well,
do you know this, for example,

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:33.800
you think of maqam bayati?

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:36.670
So all of them are maqam
bayati when you play it

00:10:36.670 --> 00:10:38.320
but the emphasis is different.

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:41.570
So they call them by name,
Swherly [assumed spelling],

00:10:41.570 --> 00:10:47.140
Nazry [assumed spelling],
Sultani, and name it.

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:51.000
Like, whether that
frame of bayati or saba.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.510
So, I remember, for
example, when they said--

00:10:54.510 --> 00:11:13.040
[ Singing ]

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:15.070
It's very haunting but sad.

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:18.270
It's like you're waiting
for something, you know?

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:21.510
And by in the north, they talk
about something else, like--

00:11:21.510 --> 00:11:26.040
[ Singing ]

00:11:26.040 --> 00:11:27.340
It's very short.

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:31.800 position:56%
Because they live in the mountains
and they do not have the surrounding

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:34.650
because of the echo of
your-- is what it counts.

00:11:34.650 --> 00:11:36.120
It's very interesting.

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:37.680
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Do they
sing words to those songs?

00:11:37.680 --> 00:11:39.010
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Absolutely.

00:11:39.010 --> 00:11:40.310
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: All right.

00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:41.860
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: And, you
know, I can bring in some song

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:44.560
but usually they talk
about their life,

00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:48.490
their love for things
or missing things.

00:11:48.490 --> 00:11:54.400
Most of them are missing things,
and because death is very profound

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:58.420
in their life, especially when
we're talking about at the south.

00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:04.360
The south has very
interesting creature I call them

00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:06.430
because they create
everything basically.

00:12:06.430 --> 00:12:08.340
I mean, historically actually,

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:10.970
the Sumerian people
who lived in the south.

00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:17.750
I mean, the Marsh actually just
last week, they announced it

00:12:17.750 --> 00:12:20.960
as a heritage of UNESCO basically.

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:22.910
I mean, it took them that years.

00:12:22.910 --> 00:12:24.210
I mean, they don't understand,

00:12:24.210 --> 00:12:29.300
this is actually what the
Sumerian civilization has started,

00:12:29.300 --> 00:12:32.510
literary there, you know,
from Ur, Lakish, and Kish.

00:12:32.510 --> 00:12:33.810
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Right.

00:12:33.810 --> 00:12:38.310
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: So, I started
with that environment of people.

00:12:38.310 --> 00:12:42.640
Nobody-- Actually my
brother is a good artist

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:44.180
and very famous artist actually.

00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:45.570
He's a visual artist.

00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:46.870
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: What's his name?

00:12:46.870 --> 00:12:49.220
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: He's named Salim.

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:53.690
And he-- My father was OK
with him because he just--

00:12:53.690 --> 00:12:56.320
you know, he's a painter but
I am a troublemaker, right?

00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:57.620
I'm the musician.

00:12:57.620 --> 00:13:05.800
When I was in the second grade,
I remember this beautiful story

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:11.790
that I was in second grade and
my teacher, he's Arabic teacher.

00:13:11.790 --> 00:13:15.050
He's not a music teacher.

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:18.780
And one day, he brought
the oud with him.

00:13:18.780 --> 00:13:20.810
And he would sing to us.

00:13:20.810 --> 00:13:23.500
He was a communist actually.

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:27.520
And, so he sings to us
and I was fascinated

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:31.010
by the sound, by the shiver.

00:13:31.010 --> 00:13:35.570
And as you know, you
know, in Middle East,

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:37.420
a teacher is like a god, you know?

00:13:37.420 --> 00:13:41.810
It is not like human
being, you know?

00:13:41.810 --> 00:13:44.420
So you cannot just look
them to the eye, right?

00:13:44.420 --> 00:13:48.240
So I was like this and I
wasn't courageous enough

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:52.200
to ask him, "Can I just touch it?"

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:55.350 position:56%
And he looked at me he said, "Sure."

00:13:55.350 --> 00:13:58.610
So I raised my hand
and he just touched it.

00:13:58.610 --> 00:14:04.810
And there is something
profound and things come to my--

00:14:04.810 --> 00:14:06.910
all of my body is just like, "Oh."

00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:09.380
In fact, they have
chill, I remember.

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:14.190
So I couldn't sleep from the hand
that touched this instrument.

00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:17.850
And next day or the day after,
I remember he brought it again

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:19.940
and I said, "Can I touch it?"

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:26.560 position:56%
Because I have this beautiful
ecstasy when I just touch this wood,

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:31.070
you know, so soft and
like it's beautiful.

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:34.860
And he looked at me and said,
"Do you want to play it?"

00:14:34.860 --> 00:14:36.640
I said, "Yeah."

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:40.300
So, he hold it to me and
he said, "Be careful."

00:14:40.300 --> 00:14:43.010
And it was like really bigger
than me, you know, the oud.

00:14:43.010 --> 00:14:47.950
So he hold it to me and
I tried to imitate him.

00:14:47.950 --> 00:14:50.950
So I put my right hand and then--

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:52.730
like this and then
I put my left hand.

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:54.240
This is exactly like him.

00:14:54.240 --> 00:15:00.100
And I was so nervous and he
strums something and he's shocked.

00:15:00.100 --> 00:15:03.460
And he said, "Wow.

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:06.680
You want to be a musician?

00:15:06.680 --> 00:15:09.500
Take it." Can you imagine--

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:10.800
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Yeah.

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:12.100
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: -- a
teacher give you ouds

00:15:12.100 --> 00:15:13.780
because of a new like instrument.

00:15:13.780 --> 00:15:15.570
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: And you never
sing or played a note before?

00:15:15.570 --> 00:15:17.130
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: No, in my life.

00:15:17.130 --> 00:15:20.700
I mean, I heard it in
the radio or TV but--

00:15:20.700 --> 00:15:22.000
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Yeah.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.100
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: So he started
