at time period who is-- has a
normal relationship with Iraq.

00:45:45.090 --> 00:45:48.250
After the invasion, everything
just collapsed, right?

00:45:48.250 --> 00:45:56.650
So the only contact to the
world was Jordan, that's it.

00:45:56.650 --> 00:46:00.480
So all the Iraqi police, they are
in Jordan, basically, you know,

00:46:00.480 --> 00:46:02.070
because that's how they do it.

00:46:02.070 --> 00:46:03.370
So I was hiding, like I said,

00:46:03.370 --> 00:46:09.320
in that time until I get this
invitation to go to Syria,

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:13.680
Damascus to do this concert.

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:18.130
Long story short, I
went to Damascus.

00:46:18.130 --> 00:46:23.020
And in Damascus, you know, when--

00:46:23.020 --> 00:46:27.870
as soon as I cross
the border, I'm safe.

00:46:27.870 --> 00:46:33.040
And they told the taxi
driver to stop, to stop.

00:46:33.040 --> 00:46:39.170
And he said, "What do you want?"

00:46:39.170 --> 00:46:41.390
I said, "To stop."

00:46:41.390 --> 00:46:49.690
So I went out of the car and--
because the minute I put my foot

00:46:49.690 --> 00:46:54.050
in the ground of Syria, this is it.

00:46:54.050 --> 00:47:01.160
There's no return to
Iraq, that's it.

00:47:01.160 --> 00:47:05.490
So, I kissed the ground
actually on Syria

00:47:05.490 --> 00:47:07.820
and getting teary at that time.

00:47:07.820 --> 00:47:09.120
And he said, "Why?"

00:47:09.120 --> 00:47:11.950
I said, "This is Damascus."

00:47:11.950 --> 00:47:15.050
The taxi driver said, "so what?"

00:47:15.050 --> 00:47:19.360
But he didn't understand
what I'm talking about.

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:23.810
It's way, way, way, way, way
difficult for him to understand.

00:47:23.810 --> 00:47:25.710
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: And
you stayed for awhile?

00:47:25.710 --> 00:47:27.630
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: It is really great.

00:47:27.630 --> 00:47:30.480
In fact, I didn't want to
leave Syria-- in Damascus.

00:47:30.480 --> 00:47:31.960
I stayed there for eight years.

00:47:31.960 --> 00:47:39.230
In fact, my first-- my wife Nada,
she was a professional journalist.

00:47:39.230 --> 00:47:44.170
And she came to interview me,
which is like one day or two days.

00:47:44.170 --> 00:47:47.910
And I looked at her, she's
a beautiful, gorgeous,

00:47:47.910 --> 00:47:50.200
you know, woman, right, Syrian.

00:47:50.200 --> 00:47:53.100
And I said, "Well, could
you please marry me?

00:47:53.100 --> 00:47:54.400
like that."

00:47:54.400 --> 00:47:55.700
[ Laughter ]

00:47:55.700 --> 00:47:57.000
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: There's
something--

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:58.300
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Just like that.

00:47:58.300 --> 00:47:59.600
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Somehow
I believe that.

00:47:59.600 --> 00:48:00.900
[ Laughter ]

00:48:00.900 --> 00:48:02.200
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: She is
gorgeous, she's beautiful.

00:48:02.200 --> 00:48:04.470 position:56%
I said, "Could you please marry me?"

00:48:04.470 --> 00:48:06.310
You know, Arabic woman, shy.

00:48:06.310 --> 00:48:09.080
And we fall in love.

00:48:09.080 --> 00:48:12.040
And I stayed for eight years.

00:48:12.040 --> 00:48:16.790
And until 2000, actually, and
I came to the United States.

00:48:16.790 --> 00:48:21.530
And back to the story of
the password-- passport.

00:48:21.530 --> 00:48:24.110
So when you're out of Syria
basically you don't need anything,

00:48:24.110 --> 00:48:26.120
you know, because you
are safe, right?

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:27.420
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Right.

00:48:27.420 --> 00:48:28.960
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: And you are
working with the opposite group

00:48:28.960 --> 00:48:30.990
and Iraqi groups who
were against Saddam

00:48:30.990 --> 00:48:33.810
and the government they don't
bother you with anything.

00:48:33.810 --> 00:48:36.530
They really welcome you.

00:48:36.530 --> 00:48:40.180 position:56%
So I don't need the passport, right?

00:48:40.180 --> 00:48:42.980
So what we do as an Iraqi,
at that time when we live

00:48:42.980 --> 00:48:45.180
in Syria, is that we fake it.

00:48:45.180 --> 00:48:47.900
The government, they told
us just to bring fake one,

00:48:47.900 --> 00:48:49.860 position:56%
and then you can leave, it's normal.

00:48:49.860 --> 00:48:53.440
Because they know where
they're going to get, you know,

00:48:53.440 --> 00:48:55.010
Iraqi-- normal Iraqi passport.

00:48:55.010 --> 00:48:57.660
So we get basically from
the north, from the Kurds

00:48:57.660 --> 00:49:00.630
who are giving them-- smuggling to.

00:49:00.630 --> 00:49:02.880
And we go on different
name, language,

00:49:02.880 --> 00:49:05.580
to Lebanon I was using
different name.

00:49:05.580 --> 00:49:12.660
So, that time when I came to United
States, I said I don't need it.

00:49:12.660 --> 00:49:14.400
So I give it to my friend Ahmed,

00:49:14.400 --> 00:49:18.660
Ahmed Hashim who was living
right now in Iraq, who was the--

00:49:18.660 --> 00:49:23.680
he's a beautiful, wonderful
scholar in French literature.

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:26.950
And now he actually has a
program, Iraq TV [inaudible].

00:49:26.950 --> 00:49:29.700
I said, "Ahmed, take it."

00:49:29.700 --> 00:49:35.410
Because the way you can get out
of Syria, you need passport.

00:49:35.410 --> 00:49:36.880
So I gave it to him.

00:49:36.880 --> 00:49:39.090
He faked it.

00:49:39.090 --> 00:49:43.390
And he went to Belgium and
he get asylum in Belgium.

00:49:43.390 --> 00:49:46.810
And he went back to Syria,
you know, just to visit.

00:49:46.810 --> 00:49:48.110
And he called me.

00:49:48.110 --> 00:49:51.310
He said, "Rahim, what will
I do with this passport?"

00:49:51.310 --> 00:49:52.920
I said, "Just give it
to Nada," you know?

00:49:52.920 --> 00:49:55.190
I was here, United States.

00:49:55.190 --> 00:49:58.170
So he gave them back my passport.

00:49:58.170 --> 00:50:05.160
You know, it's already expired, you
know, it's like long, all right?

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:09.010
So he gave it to them.

00:50:09.010 --> 00:50:13.340
Until last year, I
went back to Baghdad.

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:14.640
And I talked to Nada.

00:50:14.640 --> 00:50:16.880
I'm like, "Do you know what
happened to the passport?"

00:50:16.880 --> 00:50:18.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Nada is your wife.

00:50:18.180 --> 00:50:19.480
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Yeah, Nada my wife.

00:50:19.480 --> 00:50:21.190
Sorry, I have to clarify that.

00:50:21.190 --> 00:50:27.720
She said, "I think, Rahim, he gave
it to us and still in the house?"

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:31.830
I said, "It would be
great if I could have it."

00:50:31.830 --> 00:50:34.800
So we called him and
said, yeah, we have it.

00:50:34.800 --> 00:50:39.280
So I said, but now the-- because
the situation in Syria last year,

00:50:39.280 --> 00:50:42.670
you can't, you know,
really do normal mail.

00:50:42.670 --> 00:50:46.960
I said, can you please send it to
Lebanon and from Lebanon, you know,

00:50:46.960 --> 00:50:49.110
send it in FedEx, whatsoever,
so I can get it?

00:50:49.110 --> 00:50:50.590
So they went there and
they said, "No, no, no,

00:50:50.590 --> 00:50:56.060
we cannot send a passport
document to America.

00:50:56.060 --> 00:50:57.360
We can't."

00:50:57.360 --> 00:51:00.670
Well, what can I do?

00:51:00.670 --> 00:51:05.840
And then all of a sudden,
Nada's cousin who is working,

00:51:05.840 --> 00:51:09.070
he is the head of the
Syrian airline.

00:51:09.070 --> 00:51:11.350
He said, "I have an idea.

00:51:11.350 --> 00:51:21.250
How about we send it with a
flight attendant in Damascus, huh?

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:23.400
And soon as they go
to Baghdad we give it

00:51:23.400 --> 00:51:25.940
to somebody there and call you.

00:51:25.940 --> 00:51:28.250
You can receive it in Baghdad.

00:51:28.250 --> 00:51:29.550
Why you need it now?

00:51:29.550 --> 00:51:37.030
Go to Baghdad then
you receive it there."

00:51:37.030 --> 00:51:40.110
So, I went to Baghdad from
here, from New Mexico.

00:51:40.110 --> 00:51:41.850
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: From the
States-- Yeah, from New Mexico.

00:51:41.850 --> 00:51:48.710
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: I went back
to New Mexico and to Baghdad.

00:51:48.710 --> 00:51:51.170
Two days, Nada called
me and she said, "Well,

00:51:51.170 --> 00:51:52.860
here's the number you need to call.

00:51:52.860 --> 00:51:57.190
This is the guy who
has the passport."

00:51:57.190 --> 00:51:58.680
So, I called him and
he said, "Oh, yeah,

00:51:58.680 --> 00:52:01.050
I have this old Iraqi passport.

00:52:01.050 --> 00:52:02.840
What are you going to do with it?"

00:52:02.840 --> 00:52:04.140
I said, "Nothing."

00:52:04.140 --> 00:52:06.350
So, where do you leave blah, blah?

00:52:06.350 --> 00:52:07.650
He said I'm at this hotel.

00:52:07.650 --> 00:52:15.230
And we went, me and my brother
Salim and Hamad, my nephew.

00:52:15.230 --> 00:52:20.590
So, I went to the hotel and called
him and he's coming back down.

00:52:20.590 --> 00:52:22.610
I was waiting at the lobby.

00:52:22.610 --> 00:52:25.790
And this guy, he came and he
said my name is such and such.

00:52:25.790 --> 00:52:30.720
And he just gave it
to me, like that.

00:52:30.720 --> 00:52:34.970
So, I just-- I look at it.

00:52:34.970 --> 00:52:36.270
I was in tears.

00:52:36.270 --> 00:52:40.390
And I said, I couldn't believe.

00:52:40.390 --> 00:52:44.310
Oh, my god, this is passport.

00:52:44.310 --> 00:52:56.390
I got it from Iraq who cost my mom
$25,000, and saved another life,

00:52:56.390 --> 00:53:03.010
faked in Jordan, and I
received it in Baghdad.

00:53:03.010 --> 00:53:07.340
That's doesn't happen
in novels, really.

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:10.960
If you need to write it in a
novel, you cannot write it--

00:53:10.960 --> 00:53:17.920
the significant things about
that passport because --

00:53:17.920 --> 00:53:24.120
issued in Baghdad after 25
years, I received in Baghdad.

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:26.150
I thought about that.

00:53:26.150 --> 00:53:28.000
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: And
it had a stamp by one

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:29.580
of Iraq's most favorite artists.

00:53:29.580 --> 00:53:30.880
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Absolutely.

00:53:30.880 --> 00:53:32.180
[ Laughter ]

00:53:32.180 --> 00:53:33.480 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: A beautiful story.

00:53:33.480 --> 00:53:36.930
Was that-- You visited a
music store at one point?

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:38.230
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Yes.

00:53:38.230 --> 00:53:39.530
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: And you
returned from the States

00:53:39.530 --> 00:53:40.830
to Baghdad, what year what that?

00:53:40.830 --> 00:53:43.450
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: That was in 2004
after the invasion, actually.

00:53:43.450 --> 00:53:44.830 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: What happen there?

00:53:44.830 --> 00:53:47.370
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: This is
when the invasion happen,

00:53:47.370 --> 00:53:51.610
of course that's the only way I
was able to return back to Baghdad,

00:53:51.610 --> 00:53:53.410
because before that I can't.

00:53:53.410 --> 00:53:59.710 position:56%
And so as soon the invasion
happened and Saddam regime fall out,

00:53:59.710 --> 00:54:03.270
and now I can, I can
go back to Iraq.

00:54:03.270 --> 00:54:06.270
So I went in 2004.

00:54:06.270 --> 00:54:08.420
So, I told Salim.

00:54:08.420 --> 00:54:10.170
My brother said, you
know, what I need--

00:54:10.170 --> 00:54:14.960
I need to go to places that I
used to go, you know, coffees

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:20.340
and friends meet and talk about
politics and philosophy and music

00:54:20.340 --> 00:54:25.120
and art, and the record store

00:54:25.120 --> 00:54:28.070
where we get our cassettes
and things like that.

00:54:28.070 --> 00:54:29.910
I said, "Sure."

00:54:29.910 --> 00:54:32.150
So we went there.

00:54:32.150 --> 00:54:34.860
Tell him I need to go
L'Chaim [phonetic] Records,

00:54:34.860 --> 00:54:36.820
it's called L'Chaim.

00:54:36.820 --> 00:54:39.730
So, I told Salim, "Salim,
could you please tell him

00:54:39.730 --> 00:54:43.520
if he has Rahim AlHaj CDs."

00:54:43.520 --> 00:54:46.420
So he went there and he said,
"Do you have Rahim AlHaj CDs?"

00:54:46.420 --> 00:54:49.450
He said "Who is Rahim AlHaj?"

00:54:49.450 --> 00:54:52.100
He's Arabic what kind
of song he sing.

00:54:52.100 --> 00:54:55.740
He said, "No, no, he's not a
singer, he's an oud player.

00:54:55.740 --> 00:55:02.810 position:56%
So there's a guy behind the counter,
he heard the name, and he came to me

00:55:02.810 --> 00:55:05.940
and he said, "You mean Rahim AlHaj?

00:55:05.940 --> 00:55:07.330
The oud player?"

00:55:07.330 --> 00:55:08.630
He said, "Yes."

00:55:08.630 --> 00:55:12.100
So he went back into
the store inside.

00:55:12.100 --> 00:55:16.750
And two, three, five, six
minutes whatever, he came

00:55:16.750 --> 00:55:22.200
and he brought a cassette
with my picture in it.

00:55:22.200 --> 00:55:25.210
It's like stupid, you
know, posing like whatever.

00:55:25.210 --> 00:55:26.510
It's young.

00:55:26.510 --> 00:55:29.180
And he said, "You mean this one?"

00:55:29.180 --> 00:55:31.220
And he said to him, "Yes."

00:55:31.220 --> 00:55:34.460
In fact, this is the guy.

00:55:34.460 --> 00:55:38.940 position:56%
And he looked at me like, I couldn't
believe it-- he couldn't believe it.

00:55:38.940 --> 00:55:42.970 position:56%
So he went from there and he come to
me and he give me hug, kissing me.

00:55:42.970 --> 00:55:46.630
He said, "Rahim, you
don't understand.

00:55:46.630 --> 00:55:52.480
All these years during the
sanction of 13 years and more,

00:55:52.480 --> 00:55:59.640
we've been copying this record,
I mean, secretly, secretly,

00:55:59.640 --> 00:56:06.510
because it's the only voice for
us to be against Saddam regime.

00:56:06.510 --> 00:56:08.830
And it's not illegal for us to--

00:56:08.830 --> 00:56:14.030
" because it was illegal to
sell my cassettes in the stores.

00:56:14.030 --> 00:56:18.540
So I look at it and I
just, again, I cried a lot.

00:56:18.540 --> 00:56:20.480
I said, oh my god, you know,

00:56:20.480 --> 00:56:25.780
like this is like,
what, 1982, '83, right?

00:56:26.900 --> 00:56:29.820
So I look at it and he
said, "Take it, please."

00:56:29.820 --> 00:56:34.180
And I said, no, it belongs
here, not to me, you know?

00:56:34.180 --> 00:56:35.640
It belongs to Baghdad, not me.

00:56:35.640 --> 00:56:40.390
I said, what am I going to do with
a cassette in the United States?

00:56:40.390 --> 00:56:41.690
It's here.

00:56:41.690 --> 00:56:43.430
He said, "Could you please
just sign it for me?"

00:56:43.430 --> 00:56:45.610
So I signed it for him.

00:56:45.610 --> 00:56:52.270
And I thought, wow, you know,
that's how-- I left some impact.

00:56:52.270 --> 00:56:54.280
I made a difference.

00:56:54.280 --> 00:56:56.270
When this guy was telling
me, he said, "Rahim, no,

00:56:56.270 --> 00:56:59.960
we've been copying it and
give it to people who need

00:56:59.960 --> 00:57:02.160
to see Rahim AlHaj,
Rahim AlHaj, you know?

00:57:02.160 --> 00:57:04.160
And I'm not a singer,
I'm a composer, you know?

00:57:04.160 --> 00:57:05.540
I'm an oud player.

00:57:05.540 --> 00:57:07.710 position:56%
So it was really significant to him.

00:57:07.710 --> 00:57:09.190
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Do
you have a photo of that

00:57:09.190 --> 00:57:10.830
or any copies of it or anything?

00:57:10.830 --> 00:57:12.690
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: I think,
yes, I do to some degree.

00:57:12.690 --> 00:57:16.120
I mean, when I went back,
there is a mixed feeling

00:57:16.120 --> 00:57:18.030
down that time when I first visit.

00:57:18.030 --> 00:57:19.490
It was very emotional visit.

00:57:19.490 --> 00:57:22.920
I mean, different form last
visit which is last year.

00:57:22.920 --> 00:57:27.470
This because I had an idea, all
my pictures, all the pictures

00:57:27.470 --> 00:57:29.560
who was saved, and most of
them actually they destroy,

00:57:29.560 --> 00:57:33.400
just because they don't
need any document

00:57:33.400 --> 00:57:36.970
about me even though
they know who I am.

00:57:36.970 --> 00:57:41.320
Somehow they figured out.

00:57:41.320 --> 00:57:44.630
So, it came to the idea, I
said, you know, all this memory

00:57:44.630 --> 00:57:49.510
and all these pictures belong
here, not belong to me.

00:57:49.510 --> 00:57:51.610
I don't know, I get
this, now I regret it.

00:57:51.610 --> 00:57:56.940
And I have to bring-- I
mean, I get some of them.

00:57:56.940 --> 00:58:01.230
And now actually my brother, he
said-- posting them, you know,

00:58:01.230 --> 00:58:04.520
on his page, and said nobody
will know Rahim AlHaj, you know,

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:07.820
what he was, you know, seven
or eight-- the first concert,

00:58:07.820 --> 00:58:10.990
second concert in Iraq and Bagdad.

00:58:10.990 --> 00:58:12.290
That time, you know, I was--

00:58:12.290 --> 00:58:18.160
and I toured the world with the
most famous important musician

00:58:18.160 --> 00:58:20.240
in the whole planet
in oud, Munir Bashir.

00:58:20.240 --> 00:58:25.680 position:56%
And he was my teacher for six years.

00:58:25.680 --> 00:58:29.020
And I had the privilege
actually to be with him.

00:58:29.020 --> 00:58:32.300
And I had-- you know, I
was-- not just privilege,

00:58:32.300 --> 00:58:35.990
I was actually fortunate.

00:58:35.990 --> 00:58:39.860
I mean, even though actually
he was-- God bless his soul,

00:58:39.860 --> 00:58:45.160 position:56%
he believed in me as musician but
he needs me to be part of the regime

00:58:45.160 --> 00:58:51.190
and I was refused to do that.

00:58:51.190 --> 00:58:56.360
By then, I felt like every
memory, every things that--

00:58:56.360 --> 00:59:01.750
books, and pictures, letters,

00:59:01.750 --> 00:59:05.770
that belongs to them not
belong to me, to some degree.

00:59:05.770 --> 00:59:10.010
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: So,
why the United States?

00:59:10.010 --> 00:59:11.310
[ Laughter ]

00:59:11.310 --> 00:59:14.830
In the all-- the whole
resettlement experience,

00:59:14.830 --> 00:59:16.930
what are some memorable stories?

00:59:16.930 --> 00:59:19.910
&gt;&gt; Rahim Alhaj: Well, yeah,
this is really interesting--

00:59:19.910 --> 00:59:23.490
not just interesting, this
is like hilarious, actually.

00:59:23.490 --> 00:59:27.300
When I was in Syria, I wasn't
really-- want to leave Syria,

00:59:27.300 --> 00:59:34.350
because Damascus and Sham
is the most beautiful piece

00:59:34.350 --> 00:59:37.410
of land on Earth, really.

00:59:37.410 --> 00:59:43.130
I mean, I toured the world and
I saw literally all the world.

00:59:43.130 --> 00:59:51.240
But Damascus and Sham has
something as-- it's unbelievably--

00:59:51.240 --> 00:59:56.700
not normal, in a good
way not the bad way.

00:59:56.700 --> 01:00:00.080
Damascus I call like a mother,
you know, who care about her kids

01:00:00.080 --> 01:00:02.380
but she doesn't know why.

01:00:04.040 --> 01:00:07.110
There's a street you walk
in and it's 5,000 years old.

